    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-06-18T22:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-06-18T22:00:00-05:00" n="798"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d798">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/12305.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Special Agent <persName type="from">Carothers</persName> to
                        the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Extract.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">El Paso</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-06-18T20:00:00-07:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 18, 1914, 8 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>It was impossible to prevent breach between Villa and Carranza, but Villa’s plan,
                    if carried out, will not interfere with progress of revolution. His troops have
                    left Torreon for Zacatecas and will push forward toward Mexico rapidly. Whenever
                    he encounters other revolutionary leaders he will give them the option of
                    fighting under him or of going to some other division: to Gonzalez or Obregón.
                    When they reach Mexico, Villa says, he will bend to the will of all the generals
                    and deliver the presidency to whomsoever they select in a council of generals,
                    even if it be to Carranza. He does not intend hostilities toward Carranza, but
                    says he will still receive orders from him when they do not interfere with his
                    military operations.* * * I asked him his position as to mediation and he
                    replied that should the United States recommend a certain course to him it would
                    receive profound consideration as he knew the friendship that exists towards
                    Mexico and that the United States would recommend nothing that would not be
                    beneficial to the country.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Carothers</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
